## Council of Chalcedon - Epilogue
## The Legacy

label epilogue:

    # Melancholic, reflective music for the aftermath
    play music aftermath fadein 2.0

    scene bg black with fade

    # Title card
    show text "{color=#d4c4a8}{size=48}EPILOGUE{/size}\n\n{size=28}The Legacy of Chalcedon{/size}{/color}" at truecenter

    pause 3.0

    hide text with dissolve

    # Immediate aftermath
    narrator_doc "The Immediate Aftermath"

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "On November 1, 451 AD, the Council of Chalcedon concluded its work."
    narrator_doc "The bishops dispersed to their sees, carrying with them the Definition of Faith and the thirty canons."
    narrator_doc "Emperor Marcian issued edicts enforcing the council's decisions."
    narrator_doc "Dioscorus was exiled to Gangra, where he died in 454."

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "But peace did not come to the Church."
    narrator_doc "Egypt rejected Chalcedon almost immediately."
    narrator_doc "Riots broke out in Alexandria."
    narrator_doc "The imperial-appointed patriarch was murdered."
    narrator_doc "Egypt would never fully accept the council."

    nvl clear

    # The Oriental Orthodox
    narrator_doc "The Oriental Orthodox Churches"

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "The rejection of Chalcedon created a lasting schism."
    narrator_doc "The Coptic Church of Egypt maintained that Chalcedon betrayed Cyril of Alexandria."
    narrator_doc "The Ethiopian, Armenian, and Syriac churches followed Egypt in rejecting the council."
    narrator_doc "These churches - called 'Oriental Orthodox' or 'Non-Chalcedonian' - remain separate to this day."

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "They affirm 'one nature' of the incarnate Word (miaphysitism)."
    narrator_doc "They reject what they see as Chalcedon's Nestorian tendencies."
    narrator_doc "Modern ecumenical dialogues have suggested the difference may be more verbal than substantive."
    narrator_doc "But reunion has not yet been achieved."

    nvl clear

    # The Chalcedonian churches
    narrator_doc "The Chalcedonian Churches"

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "The Catholic Church, the Eastern Orthodox churches, and most Protestant churches accept Chalcedon."
    narrator_doc "The Definition of Faith remains the standard of orthodox Christology."
    narrator_doc "The four adverbs - unconfusedly, immutably, indivisibly, inseparably - define the boundaries of the doctrine."

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "The Tome of Pope Leo became a foundational document of Western theology."
    narrator_doc "The acclamation 'Peter has spoken through Leo' demonstrates the council's recognition of papal authority."
    narrator_doc "The Orthodox see the council as authoritative, though they interpret Canon 28 differently than Rome."

    nvl clear

    # Later history
    narrator_doc "Later History"

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "The Christological controversies did not end at Chalcedon."
    narrator_doc "The Fifth Ecumenical Council (Constantinople II, 553) condemned the 'Three Chapters' to reconcile the miaphysites."
    narrator_doc "The Sixth Ecumenical Council (Constantinople III, 680-681) condemned Monothelitism."
    narrator_doc "The Seventh Ecumenical Council (Nicaea II, 787) addressed iconoclasm."

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "But Chalcedon remained the touchstone."
    narrator_doc "Its formula was affirmed again and again."
    narrator_doc "Its authority was never questioned by the churches that accepted it."

    nvl clear

    # The Great Schism
    narrator_doc "The Foreshadowing of Schism"

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "Canon 28 granted Constantinople 'equal privileges' with Rome."
    narrator_doc "The Roman legates rejected it."
    narrator_doc "Pope Leo himself refused to accept it."
    narrator_doc "This dispute foreshadowed the Great Schism of 1054."

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "Chalcedon affirmed Rome's primacy when the bishops acclaimed 'Peter has spoken through Leo.'"
    narrator_doc "But some in the East would later reject papal authority over the universal Church."
    narrator_doc "The seeds of schism were planted."
    narrator_doc "Six centuries later, they would bear bitter fruit."

    nvl clear

    # Eternal significance
    narrator_doc "Eternal Significance"

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "The Council of Chalcedon answered the question at the heart of the Faith:"
    narrator_doc "Who is Jesus Christ?"

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "He is one person in two natures."
    narrator_doc "Truly God. Truly man."
    narrator_doc "The natures united without confusion."
    narrator_doc "The natures distinct without separation."

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "This answer has shaped Catholic worship, prayer, and devotion for over fifteen centuries."
    narrator_doc "When the faithful pray to Christ, they pray to one who is both God and man."
    narrator_doc "When they receive the Eucharist, they receive the Body and Blood of one who is both Creator and creature."
    narrator_doc "The Incarnation - God becoming man without ceasing to be God - is the heart of the Catholic faith."

    nvl clear

    narrator_doc "Chalcedon defined that heart."

    nvl clear

    # Final words - solemn chant
    scene bg black with dissolve

    play sound chant_kyrie
    play music solemn fadeout 1.0 fadein 1.0

